A chieftain of the All Progressives Congress (APC) in Rivers State, Kingsley Wenenda Wali, has faulted the decision of the state government to temporarily left restrictions over Coronavirus to enable Christians in the state observe the Easter celebrations. Governor Nyesom Ezenwo Wike, has in a state-wide broadcast on Thursday evening, announced that religious groups would be allowed to hold their full gatherings for the Good Friday and Easter Sunday services. But, Wali, in a statement issued in Port Harcourt yesterday, advised residents of the state to take personal responsibility, pointing out that Coronavirus does not know religion or political party. He said: “As citizens of Rivers State, take personal responsibility. Look at him closely and don’t listen to him. He has lost the plot and no longer in charge. If any religious leaders tells you to come to Church or Mosque, flee from that character because he is suicidal and also not in charge. “As far as this pandemic is concerned, we now have enough proof that it is up to us to take our destiny in our hands. Covid-19 does know religion or party and that is why Rome, Jerusalem and Mecca have been shutdown by both political and religious leaders. “For the sake of the children, your own good and that of the society, please avoid congregations and shun desperate leaders.”